<paragraph blockId="24.[132,633,1454,1478]" box="[132,633,1454,1478]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">
<collectionCode box="[132,230,1455,1478]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">MATERIAL</collectionCode>
EXAMINED. — 
<specimenCount box="[381,499,1454,1478]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" type="generic">5 specimens</specimenCount>
(see 
<tableCitation box="[547,619,1454,1478]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="6.[134,145,230,248]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. — Sampling stations, habitat sampled and species captured during our field surveys (2016-2018). Abbreviations: A, above slow-flowing steam, B, cultivated farm; C, fallow farmland; D, beside fruiting tree; E, cleared farmland; F, understory of Primary forest; G, ecotone forest/alpine grassland, H, cave; I, gap between trees; J, forest fragment; K, waterhole." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,775,1504,1634]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">
<collectionCode box="[132,229,1506,1530]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">ORIGINAL</collectionCode>
DATA. — 5 individuals of the Dwarf free-tailed bat were mist-netted over a slow flowing stream in a fallow farmland, at an altitude 
<quantity box="[213,276,1557,1581]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" unit="m" value="470.0">470 m</quantity>
a.s.l. These specimens were the first recorded in the Mount 
<collectingCountry box="[204,306,1584,1608]" name="Cameroon" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
area. We did not examine any museum specimens attributed to this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="505" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,776,1660,1896]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">
DIAGNOSIS. — The forearm measurement of this species is 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.945" metricValueMax="3.02" metricValueMin="2.87" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" unit="mm" value="29.45" valueMax="30.2" valueMin="28.7">28.7- 30.2 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[234,305,1687,1711]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="12.[134,145,220,238]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="TABLE 3. — External measurements of adult bats captured on Mount Cameroon. Measurements are given as mean ± standard deviation and range." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7">Table 3</tableCitation>
), which concurs with measurements provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[132,303,1713,1738]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" pagination="520 - 522" refId="ref26376" refString="HAPPOLD M. 2013 h. - Tadarida nanula Dwarf Free-tailed Bat, in M. HAPPOLD &amp; D. C. D. HaPPOLD (eds), The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hegdehogs, shrews and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London: 520 - 522. http: // doi. org / 10.5040 / 9781472926944.0282" type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="h">Happold (2013h)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName box="[331,487,1713,1737]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Tadarida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanula">
<emphasis box="[331,487,1713,1737]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Tadarida nanula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The dorsal and flank pelage is brown, contrasting with creamy-white chest and belly (
<figureCitation box="[650,715,1740,1764]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="24.[813,824,1398,1416]" captionTargetBox="[813,1456,216,1341]" captionTargetId="figure-439@24.[813,1456,216,1341]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIG. 17. — Mops (Xiphonycteris) nanulus J. A. Allen, 1917. Photo: © Aaron Manga Mongombe." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4060077" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4060077/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Ears are large with large flap of skin joining the inner surfaces. The wing membranes are whitish, and each jaw possesses two lower incisors. External measurements (
<tableCitation box="[370,441,1819,1843]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="12.[134,145,220,238]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="TABLE 3. — External measurements of adult bats captured on Mount Cameroon. Measurements are given as mean ± standard deviation and range." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7">Table 3</tableCitation>
) and skull measurements (
<tableCitation box="[696,767,1819,1843]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="26.[132,143,217,235]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="TABLE 4. — Cranial and dental measurements (mm) of preserved bats capture for the first time in the Mount Cameroon Region (November 2016-November 2018). Abbreviations explained in the Material and Method section." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD55A395F1C8DFF7AFD85413B" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" tableUuid="DF4C665DD55A395F1C8DFF7AFD85413B">Table 4</tableCitation>
) of one preserved bat are within the range given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[610,775,1846,1870]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" pagination="520 - 522" refId="ref26376" refString="HAPPOLD M. 2013 h. - Tadarida nanula Dwarf Free-tailed Bat, in M. HAPPOLD &amp; D. C. D. HaPPOLD (eds), The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hegdehogs, shrews and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London: 520 - 522. http: // doi. org / 10.5040 / 9781472926944.0282" type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="h">Happold (2013h</bibRefCitation>
as 
<emphasis box="[157,324,1872,1896]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">
<taxonomicName box="[157,318,1872,1896]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Tadarida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanula">Tadarida nanula</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="505" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,775,1922,2026]" lastBlockId="24.[813,1455,1488,1591]" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">
HABITATS AND DISTRIBUTION. — The Dwarf free-tailed bat is widely, but patchily, recorded in West, Central and East Africa from 
<collectingCountry name="Sierra Leone" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Sierra Leone</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[246,319,1975,1999]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Guinea</collectingCountry>
through 
<collectingCountry box="[414,522,1975,1999]" name="Cameroon" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, to western 
<collectingCountry box="[645,730,1975,1999]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
and southward to 
<collectingCountry box="[265,605,2002,2026]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Democratic Republic of the Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[618,775,2002,2026]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" pagination="520 - 522" refId="ref26376" refString="HAPPOLD M. 2013 h. - Tadarida nanula Dwarf Free-tailed Bat, in M. HAPPOLD &amp; D. C. D. HaPPOLD (eds), The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hegdehogs, shrews and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London: 520 - 522. http: // doi. org / 10.5040 / 9781472926944.0282" type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="h">Happold 2013h</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName box="[836,994,1488,1512]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Tadarida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanula">
<emphasis box="[836,994,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">Tadarida nanula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It is principally associated with lowland closed forest habitat (
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[946,1084,1514,1538]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold 1987</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[1094,1299,1514,1538]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" refId="ref28385" refString="MONADJEM A., TAYLOR P. J., COTTERILL F. P. D. &amp; SCHOEMAN M. C. 2010. - Bats of Southern and Central Africa: a Biogeographic and Taxonomic Synthesis. University of the Witwatersrand Press, Johannesburg, South Africa, 596 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1644 / 12 - MAMM-R- 184.1" type="book" year="2010">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[1203,1246,1514,1538]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="505">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
). It has also been recorded in mesic savannah (
<bibRefCitation author="Kingdon" box="[1083,1222,1541,1565]" firstAuthor="Kingdon" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" refId="ref27435" refString="KINGDON J. 1974. - East African Mammals. An Atlas of Evolution in Africa. (Insectivores and Bats). Academic Press, London." type="book" year="1974">Kingdon 1974</bibRefCitation>
), where it roosts in small colonies in roofs of thatched huts and tree hollows (
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[1299,1441,1567,1591]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="24" pageNumber="505" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold 1987</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
